{{Top|canon=Near-human}}
[[File:Neealavar.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Nee Alavar/Legends|Nee Alavar]], a [[Lorrdian/Legends|Lorrdian]]]]
{{Quote|Above all else, humans are ''adaptable'' — adaptable in terms of physiology, mentality and society. Their genome is remarkably elastic: Selection pressures need a few millennia at most to engage new genes and reshape their bodies in response to environmental changes, as the galaxy's countless near-human populations attest.|[[Hali Ke]], [[Kaminoan/Legends|Kaminoan]] senior research geneticist|<ref name="Star Wars: The Essential Guide to Warfare Author's Cut">{{SW|url=news/the-essential-guide-to-warfare-authors-cut-part-7-the-grand-army-of-the-republic|series=Star Wars: The Essential Guide to Warfare Author's Cut|text=Part 7 &mdash; The Grand Army of the Republic}}</ref>}}
'''Near-Human''' was the general term for any of the many [[Species/Legends|species]] or [[Subspecies/Legends|subspecies]] in [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]] which were very closely related biologically to baseline [[Human/Legends|Humans]]. In contrast, other [[Humanoid/Legends|humanoid]] species only had general external similarities to Humans, and had no biological connection. However, the term "humanoid" was sometimes used loosely to describe Near-Human species.

Most Near-Humans shared close external similarities to Humans, usually with small differences in skin and eye color or bone structure. Biologically, many Near-Humans were capable of interbreeding with baseline Humans. Some were close enough to the Human baseline to be considered a race or ethnic group of Humans, rather than a separate species. Similarly, some groups, biologically classified as Humans, though differing from the Human mainstream almost entirely in their culture, were considered so distinct that they were sometimes referred to as Near-Human.

==History==
The term "Near-Human" was used for species and races which had evolved significant physiological differences from baseline [[Human/Legends|Humanity]]. It was also occasionally used for unrelated species with substantial external similarities to Humans, such as the plant-descended [[Zelosian]]s,<ref name="Barely Tolerable 1">{{SW|url=news/barely-tolerable-alien-henchmen-of-the-empire-part-1|series=Barely Tolerable: Alien Henchmen of the Empire|text=Part 1|nolive=1}}</ref> though such use was technically improper.<ref name="Welcome to the Star Wars Jungle">{{SW|url=news/welcome-to-the-star-wars-jungle|text=Welcome to the ''Star Wars'' Jungle|int=Welcome to the Star Wars Jungle|nolive=1}}</ref>

Though Near-Humans were not Human in the strictest sense, their "almost human" status led to exceptions in the [[Speciesism|xenophobic]] and [[Humanocentrism|Humanocentric]] policies of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]]. Not all Imperials accepted Near-Humans as equals, however: [[Grand Admiral/Legends|Grand Admiral]] [[Rufaan Tigellinus]] despised high-ranking Near-Human colleagues such as the part-[[Sephi/Legends|Sephi]] [[Grand Moff/Legends|Grand Moff]] [[Bertroff Hissa]]<ref name="Barely Tolerable 1" /> and the [[Chiss/Legends|Chiss]] Grand Admiral [[Mitth'raw'nuruodo/Legends|Thrawn]].<ref name="underworld">{{Hyperspace|url=hyperspace/member/insideronline/89/indexp3.html|text=Underworld Appendix: Swoops, Spice, and Wretched Rogues|int=Underworld Appendix: Swoops, Spice, and Wretched Rogues}}</ref> Another Imperial Near-Human, Grand Admiral [[Danetta Pitta]], kept his [[Borneck]] and [[Etti]] ancestry secret while ardently supporting Humanocentrism and [[High Human Culture/Legends|Human High Culture]].<ref name="ww:iga">{{InsiderCite|66|Who's Who: Imperial Grand Admirals}}</ref> [[Calian]] [[Shockboxing/Legends|shockboxer]] [[Lobar Aybock]] recalled an Imperial saying in [[Fists Of Ion: Memoirs Of A Champion Shockboxer|his autobiography]]&mdash;"near Human, not near enough."<ref name="Fists of Ion">{{Hyperspace|url=hyperspace/fiction/feature20081031.html|text="Fists of Ion"|int=Fists of Ion|newhost=Suvudu}}</ref>

==Near-Human types==
===[[Chiss/Legends|Chiss]]===
[[File:Outboundthrawn.jpg|thumb|Grand Admiral Thrawn was a male [[Chiss/Legends|Chiss]].]]
The [[Chiss/Legends|Chiss]], a race that dwelt in the [[Unknown Regions/Legends|Unknown Regions]], were a Near-Human people<ref name="UAA">''[[Ultimate Alien Anthology]]''</ref> that had pale blue skin, generally black hair, and red reflective or fluorescent eyes which gave them excellent low-light vision. Their growth cycle differed from Humans, with an early maturation, for example. They were differentiated enough from baseline Humans to be considered a new species. In other aspects they resembled normal Humans: they bled red blood, and the cloning tanks used to [[Cloning/Legends|clone]] Human [[Stormtrooper/Legends|stormtroopers]] also worked on Chiss physiology.

===[[Zeltron/Legends|Zeltrons]]===
[[File:Zeltron.jpg|thumb|A female [[Zeltron/Legends|Zeltron]].]]
[[Zeltron/Legends|Zeltrons]] were Near-Humans<ref name="UAA" /> with a completely Human appearance, save for their skin, which normally came in shades of pink or red. This pigmentation may or may not have been a result of [[Zel (star)|their sun's]] highly radioactive rays. Generally speaking, they actually were a rather amorous race, famous (or infamous) for their many sculptures and paintings on the subject. Along with their above-average looks, Zeltrons could use telepathy and powerful pheromones to influence other beings with relative ease. They also made great strides in the field of [[Hologram/Legends|holograms]] and were responsible for the ones used at [[Hologram Fun World]]. Zeltrons were differentiated enough from baseline Humans to actually be considered a new species.

===Others===
[[:Category:Human and Near-Human species|Many other Near-Human races]] existed, each with their own similarities to and differences from the Human baseline. The [[Pau'an/Legends|Pau'an]] and [[Utai/Legends|Utai]] species of the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Utapau/Legends|Utapau]],<ref name="ROTS Novel">[[Star Wars: Revenge of the Sith (novelization)|''Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith'' (novel)]]</ref> and the [[Sullustan/Legends|Sullustans]] of [[Sullust/Legends|Sullust]]<ref name="MF">[[Millennium Falcon (novel)|''Millennium Falcon'']]</ref> were among the species which, despite outward appearances, were classified as Near-Humans. The [[Zelosian]] species, though classified as Near-Humans,<ref name="c">''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''</ref> were in fact sentient, mobile plants. By contrast, other Near-Humans were close enough to baseline Humans to be identified as [[:Category:Human races|sub-groups of the Human species]] by some sources. These included the [[Hapan]]s and the [[Lorrdian/Legends|Lorrdians]].<ref name="Alien Encounters">''[[Alien Encounters]]''</ref>

==Non-Human parallels==
Humans were not the only [[Sentience/Legends|sentient]] species to develop into several distinct races. The [[Duros/Legends|Duros]], for example, gave rise to several [[Near-Duros]] races, such as the [[Neimoidian/Legends|Neimoidians]]. Other pairs of closely related species included: the [[Xexto/Legends|Xexto]] and the [[Quermian/Legends|Quermians]]; the [[Horansi]] subspecies; the many races of the [[Nikto/Legends|Nikto]] species; the [[Ranat/Legends|Ranats]] and the [[Tintinna/Legends|Tintinna]]; the [[Ssi-ruu]]k and [[P'w'eck]]; the [[Sith (species)/Legends|Sith]] and the [[Massassi/Legends|Massassi]]; the [[Zolander]]s and the [[Clawdite/Legends|Clawdites]]; the [[Ewok/Legends|Ewoks]] and [[Dulok/Legends|Duloks]]; the [[Troob]] and the [[Hobor]]s, and the [[Trandoshan/Legends|Trandoshans]] and the [[Saurin/Legends|Saurin]]. The [[t'landa Til]] and the [[Hutt/Legends|Hutts]] were also related to one another, though more distantly. Although unsubstantiated, some in the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] speculated about a possible connection between the [[Yevetha]] and the [[Twi'lek/Legends|Twi'leks]].<ref name="Before the Storm">''[[Before the Storm]]''</ref>

==Behind the scenes==
The Near-Human status of many "alien races" is not always certain. For instance, aliens who appear very similar to Humans may often be assumed by fans to be Near-Human, though this may never be explicitly stated in the [[canon]]. The confusion is compounded by the absence of any canonical explanation of what precisely "Near-Human" means. The definition could be as broad as a humanoid creature about the same size and bone structure of a Human, or could be more specific such as being able to biologically reproduce with a Human.

From a production perspective, many characters in the ''Star Wars'' universe are human actors wearing makeup, masks, or prosthetic appliances, making it difficult and expensive to create races that could not be a Human in a costume.

